description: Otospermophilus beecheyi or Otospermophilus variegatus

Osprey with Shad dinner. I totally lucked out as my wife and I pulled over to take some scenic coastal photos and stretch our legs, and we almost immediately witnessed this Osprey dive into the shallow surf zone maybe 10 yards off of the beach below, and start to fly up towards us with this captured Shad.  I was so excited that I didn't completely focus the best photo of all.
American Shad caught by Osprey from surf zone near mouth of Russian River.
Spotted this Osprey flying along coast with a Rockfish meal. It turned inland and flew into the tall pine trees, probably where its nest and mate were.

description:
Not really B. pinophilus, see the notes for the species name for more info on that. But calling B. pinophilus for now. Oh, one of the hallmarks of this species can be seen in the second photo, they tend to grow in clusters, although obviously not always. I think this is one of the only boletes that grow in clusters?

There were only these tight buttons found up there this weekend, so it wasn’t quite bolete season yet.

Unfortunately, as is usual with the edibles on these forays, the base of these have been trimmed. Actually I often find it hard to even get a photo of good edibles, so I had to make do with these trimmed samples.

These are sugar pine cones, the real big ones, and a few of the good scales chosen for the tiny mushrooms. These are fairly common, but I believe only discovered about seven years ago. description:
Found when someone was putting up his tent, and these were in the way. People thought they were A. albolutescens buttons. But cutting them open you can see the veil is much thicker at the stipe then at the cap margin. Plus the veil is splitting radially, which fits the discriptions for this species. It is one of the Cort. species where the cortina is permanent.

From the photos and comments on MykoWeb, these look more like C. magnivelatus, instead of the first id of C. verrucisporus that I got from Arora. The photos in Arora were black and white, so I can’t put to much store in those I guess.
